# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: council-tax-in-scotland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/air-departure-tax] On 20 June 2017, the Air Departure Tax (Scotland) Act 2017 was passed in the Scottish Parliament and received royal assent on 25 July 2017 and was meant to be introduced on 1 April 2018.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/air-departure-tax] However, on 22 November 2017, the UK and Scottish ministers agreed to delay the introduction of ADT until issues have been resolved regarding the tax exemption for flights departing airports in the Highlands and Islands of Scotland.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/air-departure-tax] In June 2018, the Scottish Government and UK Government agreed that it would not be possible to introduce the ADT in April 2019.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/air-departure-tax] Air Passenger Duty has continued to apply for airports in Scotland and HMRC has continued to administer APD in relation to flights in Scotland.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/air-departure-tax] On 13 January 2026, it was announced that an alternative to maintain an exemption for the Highlands and Islands from the tax had been designed.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/air-departure-tax] The tax will now apply from 1 April 2027.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/air-departure-tax] The Scottish Government intended to reduce the rate by 50%, and eventually abolish it completely once finances allowed.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/air-departure-tax] This caused concern that such a move could damage tourism in England.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/air-departure-tax] However, in 2019 the Scottish Government abandoned its plans to cut Air Departure Tax as the proposals were no longer considered compatible with Scotland's climate change targets.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/business-rates-in-scotland] The Poor Law introduced in Scotland in 1579 provided for a poor rate to be levied to fund poor relief.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/business-rates-in-scotland] The Poor Law (Scotland) Act 1845 modernized the system, and the Lands Valuation (Scotland) Act 1854 established the foundations of the modern system.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/business-rates-in-scotland] The Valuation and Rating (Scotland) Act 1956 established a system of five-yearly revaluations, undertaken by an Assessor appointed by the local authority.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/business-rates-in-scotland] In 1989, domestic properties were removed from the rating system with the introduction of the Community Charge in Scotland, later to be replaced with Council Tax.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/business-rates-in-scotland] The Local Government Finance Act 1988 amended the existing rating system in Scotland from 1990 at the same time as introducing a new system of business rates in England and Wales from 1990, and the Local Government Finance Act 1992 made further changes.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/business-rates-in-scotland] While the latter two acts applied to the whole of the United Kingdom, as the Scottish system is based on Scots law, it remains fundamentally different from the system in England and Wales.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/council-tax-in-scotland] Council Tax is collected by local authorities though part of the tax goes to Scottish Water for water and sewage services.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/council-tax-in-scotland] In general terms: The occupiers of a property are liable, regardless of tenure, or the owners if the property is unoccupied, except if the property is a 'house in multiple occupation', in which case the landlord is liable for paying the Council Tax.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/council-tax-in-scotland] Each dwelling is allocated to one of eight bands coded by letters A to H on the basis of its assumed capital value as of 1 April 1991 and newer properties than this are assigned a nominal 1991 value.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/council-tax-in-scotland] Assessment of property values is performed by the Assessor appointed by each local authority; in some cases there is a valuation joint board that covers multiple council areas.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/council-tax-in-scotland] Each local authority sets a tax rate expressed as the annual levy on a Band D property inhabited by two liable adults.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/council-tax-in-scotland] This decision automatically sets the amounts levied on all types of households and dwellings.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/council-tax-in-scotland] The *nominal Band D* property total is calculated by adding together the number of properties in each band and multiplying by the band ratio.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/council-tax-in-scotland] So 100 Band D properties will count as 100 *nominal Band D* properties, whereas 100 Band C properties will count as 89 *nominal Band D* properties.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/council-tax-in-scotland] Each collecting authority then adds together the Band D amounts for their area (or subdivisions of their area in the case, for example, of civil parish council precepts) to reach a total Band D council tax bill.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/council-tax-in-scotland] To calculate the council tax for a particular property a ratio is then applied.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/council-tax-in-scotland] A Band D property will pay the full amount, whereas a Band H property will pay 245% of that figure.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/council-tax-in-scotland] Under Scottish Law, it is the responsibility of the tax payer to prove that the tax has been paid, not for the council to prove that it has not.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/council-tax-in-scotland] John Wilson MSP presented an Enforcement of Local Tax Arrears (Scotland) Bill on 19 March 2010 in order to try to reduce this collection time from 20 to 5 years.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/council-tax-in-scotland] Although Wilson's bill has not made any progress (as of October 2016), the Scottish parliament has passed the Community Charge Debt (Scotland) Bill to stop Councils pursuing debts from the older Community Charge, though there are some scrutiny stages to go through before it can become law.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] A **house in multiple occupation (HMO)**, or a **rooming house**, is a residential property occupied by more than one household which have shared 'common areas'.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] In the United Kingdom, this is called a 'house of multiple occupation', in North America 'a rooming house' and in Germany a 'Wohngemeinschaft'.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Most such homes have been subdivided from larger houses designed for and occupied by one family.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Some housing legislation makes a distinction between buildings occupied mainly on long leases and those where the majority of the occupants are short-term tenants.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] The legislation has its origins in fire safety legislation, following a series of publicised, preventable deaths in overcrowded buildings.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] A multiple occupancy house typically has a bathroom which is shared by all tenants.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Some may also have a common kitchen whereas others provide kitchenettes for each occupant.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Contractually speaking common areas may also include stairwells, gardens and landings.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Houses may be divided up into self-contained flats, bed-sitting rooms or simple lodgings.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] A study of rooming houses in Ottawa, Ontario, in 2016 found that "many units are in very poor condition", with issues such as mould, cockroaches, bedbugs, and broken locks.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] An article about Montreal rooming houses stated that the units often contain bedbugs and "faulty plumbing".
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Rooming houses tend to be located in places close to access, amenities and markets.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Specialist builders tend to build up to nine high-standard, low-maintenance micro apartments where once a single occupancy dwelling would have returned just one rental.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] In one Ottawa study, more than 50% of the occupants in rooming houses were found to have mental health diagnoses.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] A 1998 study of Toronto rooming house residents found that they had poorer health than the general population and low incomes.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] An article about rooming houses in Montreal stated that rooming houses are the "last stop before the street" for low-income people at risk of homelessness.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] In the United Kingdom, after a series of deaths in overcrowded houses, legislation was introduced ensuring they have a higher standing of fire-proofing to be legally compliant.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] According to the Campaign for Bedsit Rights, three people a week died in fires in houses in multiple occupation between 1985 and 1991.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Multiple occupancy dwellings were principally defined by the Housing Act 1985, as being "...a house which is occupied by persons who do not form a single household".
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Both the 1985 and the 1989 Acts were superseded by the Housing Act 2004, which established a more complete and complex definition and also introduced the requirement for some multiple tenant houses to be subject to mandatory licensing (see below).
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] The Housing Act 1985 was a consolidating act.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] The definition of HMO in section 345 HA85 was from section 129(1) of the Housing Act 1974.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] The Housing Act 2004 introduced mandatory licensing for large HMOs which were defined in the Act as properties with five or more tenants forming more than one household sharing facilities such as kitchen, bathroom and/or toilets over three or more floors.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] On 1 October 2018, the Licensing of Houses in Multiple Occupation (Prescribed Description) (England) Order 2018 amended the large HMO definition in the 2004 Act by abolishing the "3 or more floors" requirement.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Nevertheless, purpose-built flats in a block of three or more such flats were excluded from the amended classification.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Apart from the statutory definition of HMOs requiring a mandatory licence, local authorities have the power to introduce approved licensing schemes which include smaller HMOs as licensable.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Typically these are for three or more tenants forming more than one household.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] This classification helps bring buildings with inadequate fire and safety regulations under the control of local authority (LA) inspection regimes.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Section 257 HMOs are often expressly included in LA additional licensing schemes for HMOs.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] The Council Tax (Liability for Owners) Regulations 1992 provide a different definition of HMO that is used solely for determining Council Tax liability.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Typically, the landlord is required to pay Council Tax on behalf of tenants.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] HMO schemes have been subsequently introduced to other parts of the UK, though the legal definition of what constitutes an HMO varies between Scotland, Northern Ireland, England, and Wales.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Definitions of what constitutes an HMO and a household are set out in the law for each legal jurisdiction.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Before 1 October 2018, there was an additional criterion that the building was three or more storeys.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Landlords of large HMOs must apply for a licence and must comply with certain standards and obligations.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] HMOs do not need to be licensed if they are managed or owned by a housing association or co-operative, a council, a further education institute or student housing provider, a health service or a police or fire authority.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Where an Article 4 direction has been applied by a local authority, planning permission is required for the change of use of a dwelling house to HMO accommodation in the area designated.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] This is usually to protect the housing mix in particular areas of a city; for example in Newcastle upon Tyne article 4 directives have come into force in parts of Heaton, Jesmond, South Gosforth, Sandyford and Spital Tongues.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] In England and Wales, local authorities manage and enforce the licensing of HMOs.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Failure to apply for or comply with the terms of a licence for an HMO constitutes a criminal offence.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Tenants may be able to recover up to 12 months' rent from an unlicensed HMO landlord.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Since the Housing and Planning Act 2016 (HaPA), tenants can make a Rent Repayment Order (RRO) application directly against the landlord and without waiting for the council to prosecute first (the situation under the Housing Act 2004 (HA)).
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Some tenants have been successful in recovering rent from landlords of unlicensed HMOs.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Northern Ireland is a separate legal jurisdiction within the UK and all HMOs must be registered and must comply with certain standards and obligations.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] In Northern Ireland a property is an HMO if three or more people live in it, these people form at least three separate families or households and at least one person is paying some form of rent to live in the property.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] New regulations came in to force in April 2019 and a new licensing scheme managed by local councils has replaced the centralised registration scheme.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Landlords must pass a fit and proper persons test; fixed penalties have been introduced HMO managers have to adhere to a Code of Practice.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Multiple tenant house licensing was first introduced in Scotland in 2000.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] To be granted a licence under the scheme, properties must meet certain standards, such as presence of smoke detectors and fire doors.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] These provisions were included in response to a fatal fire at a student flat in Glasgow, which had no working smoke detectors, and metal bars preventing escape through a window.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Scotland is a separate legal jurisdiction within the UK and all HMOs must be registered and must comply with certain standards and obligations.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] An HMO in Scotland is a property that is shared by three or more tenants who are not members of the same family or household.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] The landlord must be "a fit and proper person" and there are annual inspections to check the property (2006 Act).
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Hostels and halls of residence for students or nurses are considered to be HMOs in Scotland and the Scottish Government is considering extending the definition of an HMO.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] At the end of March 2019 there were over 15,600 licences in force and 87% of these were accounted for by the four major cities and the Fife local authority (Aberdeen, Dundee, Edinburgh and Glasgow).
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Edinburgh accounts for almost two in five of Scotland's HMO licences due to its higher rents, large student population, tourist lets and young professionals sharing.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Shared house living spaces are often smaller but typically cheaper than a one-bedroom flat.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Tenancy agreements often include most utility bills with the rent, because it is difficult for landlords to apportion the cost of bills to each tenant fairly and it is also more appealing to potential tenants.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Shared houses are popular with buy-to-let investors because, it is believed, they have higher income-generating potential than ordinary or 'vanilla' buy-to-let properties.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] By splitting single properties into multiple bedsits that are each let out on separate tenancy agreements, landlords can also reduce their exposure to loss of earnings through rental arrears or voids.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Whilst some argue that investment is necessitated by insufficient housing supply others claim that it is exploiting it.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Although shared accommodation can improve affordability and community engagement, critics argue that it may accelerate gentrification or reduce access to long-term tenancies.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Some cities such as Barcelona and Berlin have introduced regulations defining minimum unit sizes and tenancy protections to prevent speculative use.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Proponents contend that with proper regulation, co-living can help cities repurpose underused buildings and provide flexible accommodation for transient workers, students, and newcomers.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Due to the additional legal requirements placed upon HMO landlords, many buy-to-let mortgage lenders refuse to finance HMO properties.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] This has led to the emergence of a specialised HMO mortgage market, catered for by a smaller subset of lenders.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Because the choice of products is narrower, HMO mortgage borrowers are often subject to stricter criteria.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Often they need larger cash deposits, as the average loan-to-value ratio is slightly lower than for an ordinary buy-to-let mortgage, while the minimum property value tends to be higher.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] Borrowers who are financing unlicensed HMOs may also be required to prove that their local authority has no intention to license the property in the future.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/house-in-multiple-occupation] It is also common for HMO mortgage lenders to levy stipulations on various aspects of the property, including the number of rooms permitted, the type of tenancy agreement and the type of locks installed on internal and external doors.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/land-and-buildings-transaction-tax] LBTT is a tax applied to residential and commercial land and buildings transactions (including commercial purchases and commercial leases) where a chargeable interest is acquired.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/land-and-buildings-transaction-tax] Under the **Land and Buildings Transaction Tax (Scotland) Act 2013** (asp 11), a land transaction must be notified to Revenue Scotland unless it falls within one of the exempt categories contained in the Act.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/land-and-buildings-transaction-tax] Revenue Scotland administers and collects LBTT with support from Registers of Scotland.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/land-and-buildings-transaction-tax] LBTT is usually paid by the solicitor on behalf of the buyer, as part of the administrative process to complete the conveyancing transaction, although final responsibility lies with the buyer.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/land-and-buildings-transaction-tax] Submitting an LBTT return and making arrangements to pay the LBTT due is a prerequisite to applying for registration of title.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/land-and-buildings-transaction-tax] LBTT is a progressive tax, with its structure designed so that the charge rises more than proportionately to the actual price of the property.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/land-and-buildings-transaction-tax] The percentage rate for each band in LBTT is applied only to the part of the price over the relevant threshold and up to the next threshold.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/land-and-buildings-transaction-tax] Proposals for rates and bands were announced by the Cabinet Secretary for Finance, Employment and Sustainable Growth on 9 October 2014, as part of the annual Draft Budget process and tax calculators are available to help taxpayers and agents determine the amount of LBTT due.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/land-and-buildings-transaction-tax] The proposed tax rates and bands are subject to consultation and parliamentary scrutiny through the Draft Budget process, led by the Finance Committee of the Scottish Parliament.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/land-and-buildings-transaction-tax] The Cabinet Secretary for Finance, Constitution and Economy announced on 21 January 2015 that he had reviewed the proposed rates and bands for residential property transactions.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/land-and-buildings-transaction-tax] By 2018, an estimated 90% of Scottish home buyers were paying a smaller amount or the same, compared with stamp duty.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/land-and-buildings-transaction-tax] Generally, leases of residential property will be exempt from LBTT.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/land-and-buildings-transaction-tax] For non-residential leases, Schedule 19 of the Land and Buildings Transaction Tax (Scotland) Act will apply.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/land-and-buildings-transaction-tax] LBTT will be charged on both the rent and any other consideration paid for the lease.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/land-and-buildings-transaction-tax] The LBTT on the rent will be payable on the net present value of the rent, and will be subject to a three yearly review that will ensure that the LBTT paid reflects the rent paid.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/land-and-buildings-transaction-tax] Generally, leases of residential property are exempt from LBTT.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/land-and-buildings-transaction-tax] LBTT may also be payable on chargeable consideration other than rent, such as a premium.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/local-government-finance-act-1992] The **Local Government Finance Act 1992** (c.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/local-government-finance-act-1992] 14) is an act of the Parliament of the United Kingdom.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/local-government-finance-act-1992] The act includes obligations of the occupants or (in the case of vacant properties and houses in multiple occupation) the owners of properties in the United Kingdom (except Northern Ireland) to pay Council Tax.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/local-government-finance-act-1992] It repealed large sections of the Local Government Finance Act 1988, which introduced the unpopular Community Charge (known as the "poll tax"), which was replaced by the new Council Tax.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/local-income-tax] Several political parties have advocated a **local income tax in Scotland** as an alternative to the Council Tax, as part of funding for local authorities.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/local-income-tax] Various proposals were promoted during the 2007 general election campaign.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/local-income-tax] In 2004, the Scottish Socialist Party launched a "Scrap the Council Tax" campaign, boosted by a poll suggesting 77% of Scots supported the abolition of the tax.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/local-income-tax] A bill proposing a progressive system of taxation based on a household's income was presented in 2005, but was defeated with 12 MSPs in favour, 94 against, and 6 abstaining.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/local-income-tax] Different proposals to abolish council tax formed part of the manifestos of the Scottish National Party and the Liberal Democrats during the Scottish Parliament general election of May 2007.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/local-income-tax] The SNP version involves the centralised distribution of funds raised from the new tax throughout the Scottish local authorities whereas the Liberal Democrats' proposal devolves the distribution to individual authorities.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/local-income-tax] The SSP said under its proposals, unlike other local income tax schemes, the set-up costs and problems of fiscal flight would be insignificant, as the tax rates are not set locally.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/local-income-tax] After the 2007 election, the SNP-run Scottish Government planned to bring forward legislation to replace Council Tax with a local income tax as part of the funding for Scottish local authorities.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/local-income-tax] A major setback took place when the UK government said it would withhold almost £400 million in Council Tax Benefit if the Scottish government implemented the proposals.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/local-income-tax] Controversially, the UK government said it would, however, release the funds for a tax scheme designed by Scottish Labour.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The **Community Charge**, colloquially known as the **poll tax**, was a system of local taxation introduced by Margaret Thatcher's government, whereby each taxpayer was taxed the same fixed sum (a "poll tax" or "head tax"), with the precise amount being set by each local authority.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] It replaced domestic rates in Scotland from 1989, and from 1990, it was introduced into England and Wales.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The repeal of the poll tax was announced in 1991, and in 1993, the current system of the Council Tax was instated.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Since the 1970s, the Conservative Party under Thatcher aimed to do away with the domestic rating system, which funded local government by levying taxes based on property valuation.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] By the 1980s, the system had become a significant point of friction between several Labour-controlled local councils and Thatcher's government, the latter of whom sought to limit the taxation and spending powers of the former via the Rates Act 1984.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] At the same time, criticism mounted that the periodic revaluations required by the rating system were not being carried out effectively.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The Charge replaced the rating system's valuation-based tax on property with a fixed tax on individuals, with limited adjustment for a person's financial circumstance.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] As such, it was viewed as regressive and engendered public opposition.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Tens of thousands attended demonstrations that sometimes boiled over into riots, the largest of which injured more than 100 in Trafalgar Square on 31 March 1990.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Local councils often struggled to collect the tax, especially in areas with large numbers of transient renters.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Many individuals avoided or actively resisted payment, and in England and Wales an estimated £1.2 billion went uncollected in the first year of the Charge.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The tax proved to be a stake through the heart of Thatcher's premiership.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] In the 1990 Conservative Party leadership election, she lost on the first ballot to three contenders who all vowed to abolish the Charge.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Its replacement with the Council Tax, based on property valuation, was announced by the Conservative government of John Major in 1991 and enacted on 1 January 1993.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Some councils chased poll tax arrears for decades afterward; Scotland put an end to the practice in 2015 and wrote off a total of £425 million in debt.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] In the 1979 elections the Conservative manifesto stated that lowering income tax took priority.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The Government published a green paper in 1981 under the title *Alternatives to Domestic Rates*.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] It considered a flat-rate per-capita tax as a supplement to another tax, noting that a large flat-rate tax would be seen as unfair.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The 1980s saw a period of general confrontation between central government and Labour-controlled local authorities over levels of expenditure (known as the "rate-capping rebellion"), which eventually led to the abolition of the Greater London Council and the six metropolitan county councils.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The commitment to abolish the rates was replaced in the 1983 general election manifesto with a commitment to introduce the ability for central government to cap rates which it saw as excessive.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] This was introduced by the Rates Act 1984.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Although the rates system was supposed to have regular revaluations to minimise discrepancies, the revaluations in England and Wales had been cancelled in 1978 and 1983.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The Scottish revaluation of 1985/1986 led to a great deal of criticism and gave added urgency to rates reform or replacement.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The green paper of 1986, *Paying for Local Government*, produced by the Department of the Environment from consultations between Lord Rothschild, William Waldegrave and Kenneth Baker, proposed the poll tax.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] This was a fixed tax per adult resident, although there was a reduction for poor people.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] This charged each person for the services provided in their community.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Owing to the variations in the amount of local taxes paid and the amount of grant provided by central government to individual local authorities, there were differences in the amount charged between councils.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] It become known as the "poll tax" as this is a general term referring to a tax charged at an equal amount per head (also known as a head-tax), but also as a reference to historical unpopular head-taxes, in particular the English poll taxes of 1376–1381.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] This proposal was contained in the Conservative manifesto for the 1987 General Election.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The legislation introducing the poll tax was passed in 1988, and the new tax replaced the rates in Scotland from the start of the 1989/90 financial year and in England and Wales from the start of the 1990/91 financial year.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Additionally, the Uniform Business Rate, levied by local government at a rate set by central government and then apportioned between local authorities in proportion to their population, was introduced.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The tax was not implemented in Northern Ireland, which continued, as it still does as of 2026, to levy the rating system.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The poll tax went into effect on 1 April 1990.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] It encountered a number of administrative and enforcement difficulties.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The initial register, which was based on the rates register for "owned" houses, contained many irregularities from supplementary data sources such as housing benefit recipients.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Councils attempted to compile registers of taxpayers from sources such as the electoral register and university enrollment data.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Some renters did not pay, knowing they would have moved elsewhere by the time the bills arrived.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Councils of towns with highly mobile populations, such as university towns, were faced with big store rooms of unprocessed "gone-aways".
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The nature of the shared house market meant that not even the landlord knew exactly who was living there; tenants were replaced and may have shared a "single" room with their partner.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Therefore, the local council did not know who was living where and when.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Thatcher herself was warned in writing by Westminster City Council for failing to register for the poll tax at 10 Downing Street, reflecting widespread uncertainty among even the Charge's architects about the details of its implementation.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] A significant collection issue was the 20 per cent / 100 per cent split.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] People in employment had to pay 100 per cent, while students and the registered unemployed paid 20 per cent.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Full exemption from the tax was rare, and included the mentally disabled and members of enclosed religious orders.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Councils were burdened with the task of pursuing the large numbers of defaulters, many of whom were participating in organised resistance to the charge, and some councils attempted increasingly dramatic tactics to induce payment.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] On 15 January 1990, Strathclyde Regional Council issued 250000 summary warrants to those who had not paid.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Sheriffs who attempted to recoup the tax debt by poinding were often harassed by demonstrators, who at one point raided the Council's offices and destroyed records of nonpayers.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] There is also some evidence that the poll tax had a lasting effect of people not registering themselves on the electoral register to evade collection attempts, possibly because of the false impression that the words "poll tax" created.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] This may have affected the results of the 1992 general election, which ended in a fourth successive Conservative victory, despite most opinion polls pointing to a hung parliament or narrow Labour majority.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] In the first year of the poll tax in England and Wales, an estimated £1.2 billion was not collected.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The change from payment based on the worth of one's house to a fixed rate was widely criticised as being unfair, and needlessly burdensome on those less well-off.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Mass protests were co-ordinated by the All Britain Anti-Poll Tax Federation, other national networks such as 3D (Don't Register, Don't Pay, Don't Collect) and by hundreds of local Anti-Poll Tax Unions (APTUs), which were not aligned to any particular political grouping.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] In Scotland, where the tax was implemented first, the APTUs called for mass non-payment.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] As the tax neared its implementation in England, protests against it began to increase.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] That culminated in a number of poll tax riots.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The most serious of those was on 31 March 1990, the eve of the tax's implementation, when between 70,000 and 200,000 people demonstrated around Trafalgar Square.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The demonstration left 113 people injured and 340 under arrest, with over 100 police officers needing treatment for injuries.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] There were further conflicts and protests, but none on the scale of the Trafalgar Square riot.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] As the amount of the poll tax began to rise and the inefficiency of local councils in their collection of the tax became apparent, large numbers of people refused to pay.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Local councils tried to respond with enforcement measures, but they were largely ineffective given the huge numbers of non-payers.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] According to the British Broadcasting Corporation, up to 30 per cent of former ratepayers in some areas refused to pay.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The anti-poll-tax organisations encouraged non-payers not to register, to clog up the courts by contesting local council attempts to gain liability orders, and ultimately, not to attend court hearings arising from their non-compliance.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] In November 1990, South Yorkshire Police said they were planning to refuse to arrest poll tax defaulters, even when instructed to by the courts, because it would be "physically impossible for the police because of the large number of defaulters".
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The opposition Labour Party, at its 1988 annual conference, had decided against support for a non-payment campaign.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] In July 1991, Terry Fields, Labour Member of Parliament (MP) for Liverpool Broadgreen, and a member of the Militant tendency, was imprisoned for sixty days for refusing to pay.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] In popular culture, the punk band The Exploited featured the song "Don't Pay The Poll Tax" in their album *The Massacre*, which was released on 15 April 1990.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Over 40 people collaborated on Punk Aide's 1989 compilations *Axe The Tax, Can't Pay Won't Pay* and *Fuck The Poll Tax*.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Oi Polloi and Chumbawamba released and toured an EP called *Smash the Poll Tax*.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] A compilation album, *A Pox Upon The Poll Tax*, was also released in 1989.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The Orchids released "Defy The Law" in response to the Poll Tax.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] On their 22 March 1990 *Top Of The Pops* appearance, Orbital performed "Chime" while wearing hoodies with a crosshair and seemingly abstract images on them.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Upon closer inspection, those images read "no poll tax".
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] After the poll tax was announced, opinion polls showed the Labour opposition opening a strong lead over the Conservative government.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Following the Poll Tax Riots, Conservative ministers contemplated abolition of the tax but knew that, as a flagship Thatcherite policy, its abolition would not be possible while Thatcher was still Prime Minister.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Kinnock had vowed to abolish the poll tax if he won the next general election.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] For this, among other reasons, Thatcher was challenged by Michael Heseltine for the Conservative leadership in November 1990.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Although she prevailed by a margin of fifty votes, she narrowly missed the threshold to avoid a second vote, and on 22 November 1990 she announced her resignation after more than a decade in office.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] All three of the contenders to succeed her pledged to abandon the tax.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The successful candidate, John Major, appointed Heseltine to the post of Environment Secretary, responsible for replacing the poll tax.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] In early 1991 the Chancellor of the Exchequer, Norman Lamont, announced a rise in Value Added Tax from 15 to 17.5 per cent to pay for a £140 reduction in the tax.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The abolition of the poll tax was announced on 21 March 1991.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The Conservative government was re-elected for a fourth successive term in office at the 1992 general election, shaking off the strong challenge from the Labour Party.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The Labour Party leader, Neil Kinnock, resigned, having seen his party defeated in this way.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The Local Government Finance Act 1992 replaced the Community Charge with the Council Tax, and went into effect from 1 January 1993.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Council Tax strongly resembled the domestic rates system that had been in effect prior to the poll tax.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The main differences (at the Council Tax's inception) were that properties were placed in bands based on a range of property values, thereby capping the maximum amount, and that the tax was levied on the property's capital value rather than on its notional rental value.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] Households with only one occupant were also entitled to a 25 per cent discount.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The only substantial change since the introduction of the Council Tax form of direct taxation is the gradual introduction of certain exemptions and discounts.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The Scottish government continued to collect poll tax debt for two decades after the Charge was abolished.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The government collected £396000 in 2013, and in 2014 figured that more than £425 million of debt was outstanding.
[src:council-tax-in-scotland/poll-tax-great-britain] The following year, the remaining debt was written off with the passage of the **Community Charge Debt (Scotland) Act 2015** (asp 3).
